"""

We need to produce answer: reaction center identification.

We have SMIRKS: "C1CC[CH+:20]CC1.[Cl-:10]>>C1CC[CH:20](CC1)[Cl:10]"

Interpretation: Reactants: a cyclopentyl cation? Actually C1CC[CH+:20]CC1 is a cyclohexane? Let's parse: C1CC[CH+:20]CC1 is a cyclohexane ring with a positively charged carbon at position? C1 C C [CH+] C C1 forms a six-membered ring (cyclohexyl cation). The chloride anion [Cl-:10] is separate. Product: C1CC[CH:20](CC1)[Cl:10] is a cyclohexane where the carbon (formerly cation) now attached to a chlorine substituent (Cl) and also attached to the rest of ring (makes it a chlorocyclohexane). Actually product: C1CC[CH:20](CC1)[Cl:10] indicates the carbon (atom 20) is attached to chlorine (atom 10) and also to the rest of ring (makes a substituent).

